Nepal
- National. 11 Nov 2017. Massive Dengue Outbreak (Sarlahi, Mahottari, Dhading, Jhapa, Rupandehi, Kathmandu districts). As of Sep. 2017, nearly 500 hundred patients infected with dengue virus have visited Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital (STIDH). The majority of these patients were from different parts of the country particularly Sarlahi, Mahottari, Dhading, and Rupandehi districts. Very recently, at least 5 residents of Kathmandu were found to have contracted dengue virus, and they had no recent history of travel outside Kathmandu valley. However, so far, no information is available on the serotype/s of the dengue virus/es that is/are currently circulating in Nepal. This is the largest ever-recorded number of dengue-infected patients at STIDH. It shows that the government of Nepal is not well prepared for dengue outbreaks, though such dengue outbreaks have been observed, since 2006 [1,2]. Public health education (in local language) and local community involvement is critical to reduce dengue transmission, especially where mosquito density is highest or being spread elsewhere in Nepal.
Reference
1. Malla S, Thakur GD, Shrestha SK, Banjeree MK, Thapa LB, Gongal G, et al. Identification of All Dengue Serotypes in Nepal. Emerg Infect Dis. 2008;14(10):1669-70.
2. Pun SB. Dengue: An emerging disease in Nepal. J Nepal Med Assoc. 2011; 51(184): 203-8.
Contributed by :
name: Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun, MD,PhD
affiliation: Clinical Research Unit, Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital, Kathmandu, Nepal.
email: <drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

- National . 21 Nov 2017. Dengue is spreading fast in Nepal, in what could be the worst and most explosive epidemic since 2010. A few days ago, a patient diagnosed with dengue virus was airlifted to Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital (STIDH) for treatment. Another patient was brought to Kathmandu after she was confirmed to have contracted dengue virus. These 2 representative cases reflect panic among patients who are currently experiencing dengue-like symptoms, especially in the worst dengue-affected areas.
http://www.myrepublica.com/news/31113/?categoryId=81
Contributed by : Dr Sher Bahadur Pun. <drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

- Khatmandu.30 Oct 2017. The number of people suffering from dengue fever is on the rise in Mahottari. More than 400 people have been infected with the mosquito-borne disease in the past few months. Health officials said Bardibas Hospital, Swastik Hospital and Janasewa Hospitals in the district are overwhelmed by people having dengue symptoms these days. The District Health Office has, meanwhile, issued an advisory, urging the people to clean their surroundings and get rid of stagnant water where mosquitoes breed.
http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-10-30/dengue-fever-on-the-rise-in mahottari.html

