Belgium Ex Egypt. 8 Nov 2017. On November 7th 2017 a 37-year-old lady presented in Brugge, Belgium, with dengue fever acquired in Hurghada, Egypt.
Contributed by: dr. Stefaan Vandecasteele <Stefaan.Vandecasteele@azsintjan.be>
Austria Ex Egypt. 21 Nov 2017. We report a case of confirmed dengue fever in Austria acquired in Hurghada/Egypt. A 54-year-old Austrian returned from a 16-day-vacation in Hurghada to Vienna on October 29, 2017. On the 4th day after his return he complained about general weakness, abdominal pain and slight diarrhea. On November 9th he visited a surgical outpatient department, where a complete medical check-up yielded laboratory signs of a viral infection (thrombopenia 60G/l, leukopenia 3.6 G/l, elevated liver enzymes). He denied having a fever; however, we discovered an erythema on his back. Although diagnosis of dengue fever in tourists returning from Egypt is very unusual, we performed virological tests: NS1-antigen test and dengue hemagglutination inhibition test (HHT) have been carried out, both proved (highly) positive. (Dr. Eva-Maria Geringer, Department of Virology, Medical University of Vienna, Austria) On following visits all his complaints had disappeared and laboratory parameters returned to normal range. Our patient spent his holiday in a beach resort in Hurghada, he denies having been on any tours or trips outside of his resort. His flight route was without any stopover. From our point of view this has a potential impact on travel medicine advice: repellents should be recommended for travels to Hurghada and all febrile illnesses returning from Egypt should be evaluated for dengue fever.
Contributed by : Szell Marton <marton.szell@wienkav.at>

